p.text:
Subject to the threshold requirements that the documents sought must be either “referred to” in a relevant court document or “clearly identified”, the obligations imposed by a notice to produce under the present rule are similar to those imposed by a subpoena. Consequently the considerations that apply to the setting aside of subpoenas (see 
[33.4.10]–[33.4.65]
) are potentially applicable to notices to produce. In practical reality the threshold requirements for notices under the present rule (in contrast to notices issued under UCPR 
r 34.1
) are likely to minimise the occasions where it would be material to invoke those considerations. Nevertheless there remains the potential to set aside a notice to produce in particular circumstances: Bailey v Beagle Management Pty Ltd (2001) 105 FCR 136; 182 ALR 264; [2001] FCA 60;  BC200100211 ; Portal Software International Pty Ltd v Bodsworth [2005] NSWSC 1115;  BC200510136 at [10] ; Tony Azzi (Automobiles) Pty Ltd v Volvo Car Australia Pty Ltd [2006] NSWSC 283;  BC200602227 at [4]  (notice to produce set aside — very short notice, burdensome requirements, unreasonable and vexatious, sought to go behind discovery and/or seek further discovery, documents sought of questionable relevance); Siewa Australia Pty Ltd v Seeto Financial Services Pty Ltd [2008] NSWSC 305;  BC200802397  (notice to produce set aside — notice to produce sought to go behind the discovery process or to broaden it by seeking documents relating to an email discovered in separate proceedings); Hamod v New South Wales (No 8) [2008] NSWSC 125;  BC200800786  (notices too broad and long — set aside as oppressive and an abuse of process).
